  notesEn:"Nietzsche does not argue in the usual sense. He provokes, disrupts, and leaves behind fragments that continue to echo long after the page is turned. Nowhere is this more evident than in the declaration: God is dead.

This is not a triumphant statement, nor is it merely an attack on religion. It is a diagnosis of a deeper condition — that the foundations upon which meaning once stood have collapsed. What follows is not liberation, but vertigo. Without a given order, without a transcendent anchor, the world does not immediately become free; it becomes empty.

And yet Nietzsche refuses to stop at despair. If the old structures of meaning have dissolved, then the question shifts: not What is true? but What can we create? Meaning is no longer discovered — it must be forged.

This is where the book becomes strangely demanding. It does not comfort. It does not offer replacement doctrines. Instead, it confronts the reader with a possibility: that one must become the author of one\u2019s own values, fully aware that there is no higher authority to justify them.

Perhaps what lingers after reading is not clarity, but a kind of tension — between the weight of nihilism and the fragile, almost defiant act of affirming life anyway. Nietzsche calls this joyful science: not because it is easy, but because it dares to say yes, even after everything that once made saying yes possible has disappeared.",

  notesZh:"尼采的写作几乎不提供传统意义上的“论证”。他更像是在不断引爆一些思想，然后任由其在读者心中回响。其中最具震撼力的一句，莫过于——“上帝已死”。

这并不是一种胜利的宣告，也不仅仅是对宗教的否定，而更像是一种冷静而残酷的诊断：支撑意义的根基正在坍塌。人类不再拥有一个天然的秩序，也不再有一个超越性的锚点。随之而来的，并不是立刻的自由，而是一种眩晕般的空无。

而尼采真正激进之处，在于他并未停留在虚无之中。如果既有的意义已经崩解，那么问题便不再是“什么是真的”，而是“我们能否创造意义”。意义不再是被发现的，而是必须被创造的。

也正是在这里，这本书变得异常严苛。它不提供安慰，也不给出新的教条。它只是将一个问题赤裸地抛回给读者：在没有任何更高权威的前提下，你是否仍愿意为自己的价值负责？

读完之后，留下的或许并不是答案，而是一种持续的张力——在虚无的重压之下，是否仍能对生命说“是”。所谓“快乐的科学”，也许并不在于轻松，而在于：当一切使“肯定”成为可能的根基都已消失之后，人依然选择肯定本身。"
