  notesEn:"If The Gay Science announces the death of God, then Thus Spoke Zarathustra asks what comes after. It does not answer in the form of a system, but in the voice of a prophet — fragmented, poetic, and often unsettling.

Zarathustra descends from the mountains not to offer comfort, but to challenge. He speaks of the Übermensch — not as a fixed ideal, but as a direction: that humanity is not an endpoint, but a bridge. What we are is something to be overcome.

At the center of the book lies a difficult demand: that one must become the creator of one\u2019s own values. Without a higher order to appeal to, there is no external justification left. The weight of meaning falls entirely upon the individual.

And yet this is not merely a burden. Nietzsche pushes further — toward the idea of eternal recurrence: the possibility that one must live as if every moment would repeat infinitely. To affirm life under such a condition is perhaps the most radical form of saying yes.

Zarathustra is not easy to read, nor is it meant to be. It resists clarity, interrupts itself, and often contradicts. But what remains is a persistent call: not to understand, but to transform.

Perhaps the question it leaves behind is simple, but unbearable: if everything rests on you, would you still choose your life?",

  notesZh:"如果说《快乐的科学》宣告了“上帝已死”，那么《查拉图斯特拉如是说》所追问的，是在此之后人将何去何从。尼采不再试图解释世界，而是借查拉图斯特拉之口，发出一种近乎先知式的呼喊——破碎、诗性，却始终不安。

查拉图斯特拉从山中归来，并不是为了安慰人，而是为了动摇人。他提出“超人”，却并非一个可以抵达的终点，而更像是一种方向：人不是目的，而是一座桥梁，是某种尚未完成之物。人之为人，本身就是需要被超越的。

在这本书的核心，是一种极为严苛的要求：在没有任何更高秩序的前提下，人必须成为自身价值的创造者。没有可以依附的真理，也没有可以诉诸的权威，意义的重量，被完整地压回个体自身。

但尼采并未止步于此。他进一步提出“永恒回归”——仿佛每一个瞬间都将无限次重演。如果必须如此，你是否仍愿意重复你的人生？在这样的前提下，对生命说“是”，几乎成为一种最激进的肯定。

这本书并不试图被轻易理解。它不断打断自身，充满隐喻与反复，甚至彼此矛盾。但在所有这些不确定之中，始终贯穿着一个执拗的声音：不是去理解，而是去改变。

也许它最终留下的问题异常简单，却难以承受——当一切都归于你自身，你是否仍愿意成为你自己？"
